03970nam a22006975i 9780813550978DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135509787 a10.36019/97808135509782doi  a(DE-B1597)529403  a(OCoLC)768732013  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aKFC1196b.P35 2011eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a345.794/027702692221 aPaik, Leslie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscretionary Justice :bLooking Inside a Juvenile Drug Court /cLeslie Paik. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJuvenile drug courts are on the rise in the United States, as a result of a favorable political climate and justice officials' endorsement of the therapeutic jurisprudence movement--the concept of combining therapeutic care with correctional discipline. The goal is to divert nonviolent youth drug offenders into addiction treatment instead of long-term incarceration. Discretionary Justice overviews the system, taking readers behind the scenes of the juvenile drug court. Based on fifteen months of ethnographic fieldwork and interviews at a California court, Leslie Paik explores the staff's decision-making practices in assessing the youths' cases, concentrating on the way accountability and noncompliance are assessed. Using the concept of "workability," Paik demonstrates how compliance, and what is seen by staff as "noncompliance," are the constructed results of staff decisions, fluctuating budgets, and sometimes questionable drug test results. While these courts largely focus on holding youths responsible for their actions, this book underscores the social factors that shape how staff members view progress in the court. Paik also emphasizes the perspectives of children and parents. Given the growing emphasis on individual responsibility in other settings, such as schools and public welfare agencies, Paik's findings are relevant outside the juvenile justice system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDrug abusexTreatmentxLaw and legislationzCalifornia. 0aDrug courtszCalifornia. 0aJuvenile courtszCalifornia. 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitationzCalifornia. 0aYouthxDrug usezCalifornia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355097840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813550978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813550978/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK